english:
  title: Preface to the Collected Works of Master Mok-eun
  author: Lee Cheem
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Literary expression is virtue made manifest in the world. When harmony and goodness accumulate, their radiance cannot be hidden. Literature and statecraft flow together as one current. The tone of the age—whether it sings of sorrow or joy—rises and falls with fortune and disorder, yet all such expression serves to voice our nature and reveal what dwells within the heart. Though the forms of literature rise and fall with the times, and its rhythms shift with the customs of the land, should there appear one who is touched by the luminous spirits of heaven and earth, who comprehends the eternal interplay of yin and yang, who grasps the boundless transformations of all things—then his writing, with its majesty and elegance, its profundity and refinement, may rival the primal breath itself and match the work of creation. What need to fear the decline of ages or the turning of the wind?

    Master Mok-eun of Han-san was born with a love of learning and possessed extraordinary memory. He entered the Imperial Academy in China and completed its studies in three years, his knowledge vast and profound, his understanding complete and assured. Rising high in the examinations, he held esteemed office, then returned in glory to his homeland. He served his own country for more than forty years, rising to the rank of Minister of the Court. As the guardian of letters, all the nation's proclamations, decrees, teachings, inscriptions, and eulogies required his hand. He took upon himself the mission of reviving our learning, instructing the young with untiring devotion, explaining great principles and analyzing subtle meanings until all who heard understood with sudden clarity. Thus the study of principle and nature in our Eastern lands was illumined. Five times he presided over the civil examinations, and the renowned scholars of his age all emerged from his school. In his later years, when illness kept him from office, he received all visitors without exception—even heterodox teachers he would not turn away. Whether composing epitaphs for noble tombs, verses for feasts and farewells, or even writings for monks and those beyond society's pale, he would grant all requests. His brush flowed like water, unforced and effortless, achieving the height of refinement. His works, comprehensive and well-ordered, established him as a master among masters. His collected poems and prose—seventy volumes in all—flow rich and abundant, truly embodying that primal breath and matching the work of creation itself.

    One day his youngest son, Censor Jong-seon, came to me saying: 'My father's manuscripts are nearly ready for printing. Will you write a preface?' I replied: 'I am merely a visitor in the Master's circle, unworthy of his regard. My own learning is shallow and poor—how could I repay his kindness? How dare I presume to write a preface to his works? Yet when the Master took the examinations at the Ministry of Rites in China, the Grand Commandant Ouyang Wen-gong greatly praised his work and placed it first among all candidates—surely this was because their aims aligned and their spirits met. Those who judged his writing said: "His ideas soar with majesty, his language flows with refinement, like black clouds gathering from all directions, thunder and lightning flashing, rain and hail pouring down at once—until the clouds scatter and the rain ceases, leaving ten thousand miles of clear sky, washed clean and blue." Such is his extraordinary and uncommon power. Had those judges seen his complete works, they would certainly render the same judgment. In matters of principle, he follows the teachings of Master Zhang and Master Cheng; in literary expression, he looks down upon Su Shi and Huang Tingjian—all this was said in Hao-ting's preface. His work flows broad and vast as rivers entering the sea—all this appears in Yang-chun's preface. What could I possibly add?'
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Master Mok-eun (牧隱) is the pen name of Paek Mun-bo (1338-1407), a major Korean Confucian scholar and literary figure of the early Joseon period.
  - key: ''
    value: The Imperial Academy (辟雍) was the highest educational institution in imperial China, equivalent to a national university.
  - key: ''
    value: Ouyang Wen-gong refers to Ouyang Xiu (1007-1072), a renowned Song dynasty scholar, statesman, and literary critic.
  - key: ''
    value: Su Shi and Huang Tingjian were celebrated Song dynasty poets and calligraphers, representing the heights of literary achievement in the Chinese tradition.
